# LangChain / LangGraph Practices

Applies when writing LLM-extraction or agent-orchestration code. Where this rule
and `project-core.mdc` overlap, follow `project-core.mdc`.

## Grounding first
- Treat the LLM as an **untrusted extractor**: its output must pass Pydantic
  validation before it is persisted or used. Never trust raw model text.
- Ground answers in retrieved/stored data and cite the source (`source_url`).
- Do **not** add vector stores / embeddings. Reconcile against `data/weg.db`
  with deterministic JSON1 + exact-match (small alias table if needed).

## Structure
- Keep nodes/chains small and single-purpose; compose them, don't build monoliths.
- Define contracts with ABCs (e.g. `StructuredExtractor`) and inject dependencies
  so tests can substitute fakes.
- Lazy-import `langchain_*` / `langgraph` inside functions so the test suite runs
  offline without those optional extras installed.

## Extraction
- Use `.with_structured_output(Schema)` against the OpenAI-compatible client.
- Resolve model/base_url/api_key via `config.resolve_llm_settings` (CLI > env > default).
- Raise `ExtractionError` for transport/client failures; let the pipeline map each
  failure to an explicit `IngestStatus` instead of crashing the batch.

## State & control flow (LangGraph)
- Use an explicit, typed state schema; prefer immutable updates.
- Use conditional edges with clear termination — guard against infinite loops.
- Add retry with backoff only for transient errors (timeouts, rate limits).

## Security
- Never hardcode API keys; read from `.env` / env vars only.
- Validate and sanitize any external/user input before it reaches a prompt.

## Testing
- Pipeline/agent tests run offline: inject a fake extractor/mocked tools.
- Cover the failure paths (validation error, extraction error), not just happy paths.
